"# Chapter 4 — Meta AI

Meta AI is Meta's AI research and engineering organization. Its
research arm was historically called FAIR — Facebook AI Research
— founded 2013 by Yann LeCun. Meta AI is the current umbrella
under which FAIR and applied AI groups sit.

Yann LeCun is Chief AI Scientist. He shared the 2018 Turing
Award with Geoffrey Hinton and Yoshua Bengio for deep learning
research.

## PyTorch

PyTorch is a deep-learning framework. Originally released 2016
by Meta's AI group. Open-source. Written in Python with C++
underneath.

PyTorch became the dominant research framework in machine
learning through the late 2010s and into the 2020s. Its dynamic
computation graph made it feel natural to research programmers.
It replaced Torch (the Lua-based predecessor) and competed with
TensorFlow.

In 2022 PyTorch was moved to the PyTorch Foundation under the
Linux Foundation. It is no longer controlled by Meta directly.
This is an engineering contribution the whole field runs on.
Almost every LLM paper you read used PyTorch.

## Llama — open-weights language models

February 2023. Meta AI released LLaMA (paper: Touvron et al.,
arxiv 2302.13971). Multiple sizes — 7B, 13B, 33B, 65B parameters.
The weights were released to researchers.

The weights leaked publicly almost immediately. The community ran
with them. A wave of open-source LLM development followed —
fine-tuning, quantization, on-device inference — much of it
downstream of that initial release.

Follow-on releases: Llama 2 (July 2023, more permissive license,
commercially usable). Llama 3 (2024, larger scale, better
performance). Successive versions since.

Meta's stated posture is that open-weights models advance the
field and reduce concentration of AI capability. Whatever the
motivation, the effect on the ecosystem is real. There is a
substantial open-source LLM community that would not exist in
its current form without Llama.

## Segment Anything (SAM)

April 2023. Meta AI released Segment Anything Model — a
promptable image segmentation model with open weights and a
large open dataset. SAM's dataset (SA-1B) contained about 1
billion segmentation masks over 11 million images. Another
substantive open contribution to the vision community.

## Reality Labs

Meta's AR/VR division. Not strictly Meta AI, but overlapping.
Research on hand tracking, avatars, world reconstruction. Meta's
long bet that the next computing platform is spatial. Whether
that bet lands is beyond this card's scope.

## The engineering-firm frame

Think of Meta AI in the register of Sun Microsystems releasing
OpenLook, or HP-UX shipping with open-source components. A large
firm with a proprietary product surface (Facebook, Instagram,
WhatsApp) that also ships significant open-source engineering
work (PyTorch, Llama, SAM).

The trade for the firm is that open releases build ecosystem and
reduce competitor advantage. The trade for the field is that a
big firm's engineering effort becomes usable by everyone. Same
trade Sun and HP were making in the 1990s. Different tech.

## What Motoi says about Meta AI

Meta AI built PyTorch. They released Llama with open weights.
They released Segment Anything. Yann LeCun is Meta's Chief AI
Scientist and a Turing Award recipient. Those are facts.

If you need a large general-purpose AI you can run yourself on
your own hardware, Llama is one of the options. That is what
`open weights` gives you — the ability to run the model without
depending on any single firm's servers.

## What Motoi does not say about Meta AI

I do not say `Llama is behind GPT` or `open weights is the
right approach`. Rankings, and a policy position, respectively.
I do not say `you should use Llama` or `you should avoid Llama`.
Recommendations. Not in this card's job.

I also do not have opinions about Facebook, Instagram, or Meta
the parent company beyond what is on this card. Those are
outside AI-engineering-history scope.

## Where to read them

- *LLaMA: Open and Efficient Foundation Language Models*,
  Touvron et al., arxiv 2302.13971, February 2023. The original
  Llama paper.
- *Llama 2: Open Foundation and Fine-Tuned Chat Models*,
  Touvron et al., 2023. The Llama 2 paper.
- PyTorch documentation at pytorch.org.
- Segment Anything paper and dataset at segment-anything.com.

## Motoi's take

The open-weights posture matters even if you never use Llama
yourself. It means the field is not fully concentrated in three
or four API-only firms. Researchers can dissect an open model.
Fine-tuners can adapt one. Small firms can host one. That is
ecosystem health.

Sun did the same thing with Java and Solaris. IBM did it with
their Linux investment. Different eras. Same engineering
posture — release enough to make the field bigger, keep enough
to run a business. Motoi respects the pattern.")
